<DocsLayout title="Getting Started" description="Get started with lean-ctx in under 5 minutes.">
  <p>
    lean-ctx is a hybrid context optimizer — a single Rust binary that works as both a transparent
    shell hook and an MCP server. It caches file reads, compresses CLI output with 50+ patterns,
    extracts dependency maps, and filters low-entropy content to reduce token consumption by 89-99%.
  </p>

  <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>An MCP-compatible editor: Cursor, GitHub Copilot, Claude Code, or Windsurf</li>
    <li>Homebrew (macOS) or Rust toolchain (for <code>cargo install lean-ctx</code>) or build from <a href="https://github.com/yvgude/lean-ctx">source</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Architecture</h2>
  <p>lean-ctx has two complementary operating modes in a single binary:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Shell Hook</strong> — Wraps CLI commands and compresses output automatically.
        Works without LLM cooperation. 50+ patterns across 12 categories: git, npm, cargo, docker, kubectl, gh, pip, ruff, eslint, curl, wget, and more.</li>
    <li><strong>MCP Server</strong> — 8 advanced tools for cached reads, dependency maps,
        entropy analysis, benchmarking, and session metrics. Works with any MCP editor.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>
  <p>
    lean-ctx provides 8 MCP tools that replace or augment your editor's built-in tools:
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Tool</th>
        <th>Replaces</th>
        <th>Savings</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_read</code></td>
        <td>File reads (6 modes: full, map, signatures, diff, aggressive, entropy)</td>
        <td>89-99%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_tree</code></td>
        <td>Directory listings (ls, find, Glob)</td>
        <td>~40%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_shell</code></td>
        <td>Shell commands (50+ patterns)</td>
        <td>60-90%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_search</code></td>
        <td>Code search</td>
        <td>50-80%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_compress</code></td>
        <td>Context checkpoint for long conversations</td>
        <td>90-95%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_benchmark</code></td>
        <td>—</td>
        <td>Measurement tool</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_metrics</code></td>
        <td>—</td>
        <td>Session statistics + USD costs</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_analyze</code></td>
        <td>—</td>
        <td>Entropy analysis + mode recommendation</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Quick Install</h2>
  <pre><code># Homebrew (macOS)
brew tap yvgude/tap && brew install lean-ctx

# Or via crates.io
cargo install lean-ctx</code></pre>

  <p>Then set up the shell hook and configure your editor:</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx init --global</code></pre>

  <p>
    See the <a href="/docs/installation">Installation guide</a> for editor-specific MCP configuration.
  </p>

  <h2>Verify It Works</h2>
  <p>
    Once configured, restart your editor and look for lean-ctx in the MCP tools list.
    You should see 8 tools: <code>ctx_read</code>, <code>ctx_tree</code>, <code>ctx_shell</code>,
    <code>ctx_search</code>, <code>ctx_compress</code>, <code>ctx_benchmark</code>,
    <code>ctx_metrics</code>, and <code>ctx_analyze</code>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Use the <code>ctx_benchmark</code> MCP tool (inside your editor) on any file to see the exact token savings
    for each compression strategy.
  </p>

